<dl id="n53136e"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n53" href="#n53136e">N53 (VI.B.46)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n53all.htm#n53136e"> 136(e)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> root words of an a posteriori tongue <small>Red</small></blockquote> <dd class="well"> <ul class="list-inline" id="n53136e"><li>FW 83.11 </li><li><a href="../../flex/d/lexd.htm#n53136e">2010</a> </li><li><a href="../../flex/d/l39d.htm#n53136e">1939</a> </li><li><ms href="#n53136e">MS BL 47476a-51</ms> </li><li>JJA 49:109 <a name="dd9" href="../../ff/fdra/dda.htm#dd9">Usage</a> </li><li> <a href="../../flex/d/dd9.htm#n53136e">Draft: I.4&sect;1.9</a>/2.9</li> </ul> <blockquote class="sources"><font color="green">[Dr Henry Sweet, writing in 1907 to the Delegation Committee regarding artificial or ad hoc languages]</font> DEAR SIR, &mdash; It seems clear that the ideal way of constructing <mark>an a posteriori language would be to make the root-words</mark> monosyllabic, and build up the whole vocabulary on them, without any borrowed words; and to make the grammar a priori in spirit as well as form &mdash; independent of European grammar and parts of speech, no concord, no verbs, etc. But the result wouild be inferior to a wholly a priori system &hellip; <font color="green">[Index: Part 3]</font> <small> Otto Jespersen, <a name="OJIL" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#OJIL"><cite title="source">An International Language</cite></a> (1928) 41</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
